<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-403-225  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 403 225.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Andrew Seybold's Outlook on Professional Computing  Jan 30 1989 v7n7 p9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mass storage technology: an update.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pepper, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many users who are interested in mass storage issues are findingthat industry journalists are expending too much attention andhype on storage technologies that are too unreliable, not strongenough or not yet sufficiently viable to deserve the attention.andO;One of the most overhyped areas is optical storage, which comes inthree main types: CD-ROM, WORM and rewritable optical drives, ormagneto-optical technology.andP;  CD-ROM is basically a delivery methodand it may never evolve beyond that ability.andP;  WORM technology isbasically useful as an archival technology.andP;  Magneto-opticaltechnology has exciting potential but access times are abysmal andprices are extremely high.andP;  High-capacity micro floppy drives arethe cutting edge technology that may offer more immediate utility.andO;Two companies may be introducing the technology in 1989.andO;Currently, high-performance Winchester disks are still the bestproduct available in mass storage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Storage MediaNew TechniqueOptical MemoryCD-ROMWORMMagneto-Optical Disk Drives3.5&quot; DiskWinchester DiskIndustry AnalysisStorage Equipment.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>